  "markup": "\u003Cp\u003EWe have worked with three-person teams who launched sites larger and more ambitious than many enterprise rollouts. The pattern is consistent, and it has very little to do with working longer hours. Small teams that ship well do a few things deliberately that larger teams often forget.\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Ch2\u003ETreat the content model as the product\u003C/h2\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EThe fastest way to slow a small team down is to let the content model grow by accident. Every new field is a future migration, a future editor question, and a future source of drift. Small teams that move fast spend real time \u2014 often uncomfortable amounts of time \u2014 pruning the model before they build anything on top of it.\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Ch2\u003EAutomate the boring parts first\u003C/h2\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EDeployment, previews, content sync, accessibility checks. None of this is glamorous, but the compounding return on a one-click deploy pipeline over eighteen months is enormous. Larger teams can absorb manual steps; small teams cannot.\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Ch2\u003EWrite the editor experience down\u003C/h2\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EThe most overlooked document in any CMS project is the one that explains how editors should actually use it. A short guide \u2014 what each field is for, what \u201Cgood\u201D looks like, which decisions the CMS makes for you \u2014 prevents a surprising amount of future rework.\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Ch2\u003ESay no, in writing\u003C/h2\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003ESmall teams cannot afford to build everything that gets asked for. The ones that thrive keep a visible list of what they are choosing not to do and why. It protects focus, and it makes the eventual \u201Cyes\u201D easier to defend.\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Ch2\u003EShip something every week\u003C/h2\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003ENot every week will produce a feature. Some weeks it is a bug fix, a content update, a refactor. But a team that ships nothing for a month loses momentum quickly, and momentum is the one thing a small team cannot manufacture from a standing start.\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003ENone of this is secret. All of it is hard to do consistently. The teams that manage it tend to look, from the outside, like they are lucky. They are not.\u003C/p\u003E"
}]]></Value>
    </bodyText>
